UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2122
1 A RESOLUTION recognizing February 21, 2026, as Historic St. Paul A.M.E.
2 Church National Underground Railroad Network to Freedom Day in the Commonwealth
3 of Kentucky.
4 WHEREAS, the National Park Service has officially designated Historic St. Paul
5 African Methodist Episcopal (A.M.E.) Church as a site on the National Underground
6 Railroad Network to Freedom. Historic St. Paul A.M.E. is located at 251 North Upper
7 Street in Lexington, Kentucky; and
8 WHEREAS, built in 1826, Historic St. Paul served as an active Underground
9 Railroad station, featuring a concealed upper room and a stairwell behind the pulpit
10 where freedom seekers found refuge; and
11 WHEREAS, to help prevent freedom seekers from being discovered by tracking
12 dogs, the church purchased the adjacent city stray pen in order to mask human scent; and
13 WHEREAS, oral tradition affirms that Lewis Garrard Clarke, Lewis Hayden, and
14 others were aided through this network of protection and faith; and
15 WHEREAS, after escaping enslavement in Madison County, Lewis Garrard Clarke
16 became an internationally recognized abolitionist, freedom seeker, lecturer, and author
17 whose firsthand accounts of slavery helped shape nineteenth century antislavery thought
18 in both America and Europe; and
19 WHEREAS, Lewis Garrard Clarke spoke at Historic St. Paul A.M.E. Church in
20 1892; and
21 WHEREAS, documented newspaper accounts have established a connection
22 between Lewis Garrard Clarke and Historic St. Paul A.M.E. Church, affirming the
23 church's role within the broader freedom network. This was a key contributing factor in
24 the National Park Service's approval of Historic St. Paul's designation; and
25 WHEREAS, the Historic St. Paul A.M.E. Church served as the site of the 1897
26 funeral for Lewis Garrard Clarke. His life inspired the character George Harris in Harriet
27 Beecher Stowe’s Uncle Tom’s Cabin; and
