UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2122
1 WHEREAS, at the time of his death, Lewis Garrard Clarke received unprecedented
2 honors. By order of then-Governor William O'Connell Bradley, his body lay in state at
3 the Lexington City Auditorium (now the Lexington Opera House), the first tribute of its
4 kind ever accorded to an African American in the Commonwealth of Kentucky; and
5 WHEREAS, on February 21, 2026, the church will host a Community
6 Commemoration Service featuring Dr. Carver Clark Gayton, historian, descendant-
7 scholar, and great-grandson of Lewis Garrard Clarke, to celebrate this prestigious
8 national designation; and
9 WHEREAS, today, Historic St. Paul A.M.E. remains one of Kentucky's few
10 surviving Underground Railroad-era sites, preserving tangible links to faith, resistance,
11 and freedom;
12 NOW, THEREFORE,
13 Be it resolved by the Senate of the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of
14 Kentucky:
15 Section 1. The members of the Senate hereby recognize February 21, 2026, as
16 Historic St. Paul A.M.E. Church National Underground Railroad Network to Freedom
17 Day in the Commonwealth of Kentucky.
18 Section 2. When the Senate adjourns this day, it does so in honor, recognition,
19 and celebration of Historic St. Paul African Methodist Episcopal Church being officially
20 designated by the National Park Service as a site on the National Underground Railroad
21 Network to Freedom.
22 Section 3. The Clerk of the Senate is directed to transmit a copy of this
23 Resolution to Senator Reginald Thomas for delivery.
